### Autonomous District Councils

Ladakh retains two [autonomous district councils](/Autonomous_district_council): the [Ladakh Autonomous Hill Development Council, Kargil](/Ladakh_Autonomous_Hill_Development_Council,_Kargil) and the [Ladakh Autonomous Hill Development Council, Leh](/Ladakh_Autonomous_Hill_Development_Council,_Leh). These bodies work with village [panchayats](/Panchayati_raj) on local matters like economic development, healthcare, and education. Law and order, however, remain under the purview of the union territory administration.

### Law enforcement and justice

Ladakh falls under the jurisdiction of the [High Court of Jammu & Kashmir and Ladakh](/High_Court_of_Jammu_%26_Kashmir_and_Ladakh). The union territory has its own [police force](/Ladakh_Police), headed by a [director general of police](/Director_general_of_police).

### Ladakh in the Parliament of India

Ladakh sends one member to the [Lok Sabha](/Lok_Sabha), the lower house of the [Indian parliament](/Indian_parliament). The current MP for the [Ladakh constituency](/Ladakh_(Lok_Sabha_constituency)) is [Mohmad Haneefa](/Mohmad_Haneefa), who was elected as an independent candidate.

## Economy

The land is irrigated through a network of channels that guide meltwater from the mountains. The primary crops are [barley](/Barley) and wheat. Rice, once a luxury, is now a subsidized staple. Naked barley was the traditional staple crop, with cultivation reaching its absolute limit at [Korzok](/Korzok) on [Tso-moriri](/Tso-moriri) lake, at 4,600 meters, home to what are considered the highest fields in the world.

Historically, a minority of Ladakhis worked as merchants, facilitating trade between Punjab and [Xinjiang](/Xinjiang). This international trade dried up completely when China closed the borders. The region possesses vast hydropower potential from the Indus River, as well as significant solar and wind energy prospects.

Since 1974, tourism has become the new backbone of the economy. Although it employs only 4% of the working population, it accounted for 50% of the region's [GNP](/Gross_National_Product) by the year 2000. The numbers have exploded since, particularly after the Bollywood film *3 Idiots* showcased the beauty of [Pangong Lake](/Pangong_Tso). In 2022 and 2023, tourist arrivals exceeded 500,000, a staggering number compared to Leh's population of 31,000. This influx boosts the economy but is straining the fragile environment, causing waste management issues and exacerbating water scarcity.

## Transportation

Ladakh has about 1,800 km of roads, of which 800 km are surfaced, mostly maintained by the [Border Roads Organisation](/Border_Roads_Organisation). Two main arteries connect Ladakh to the rest of India: [NH1](/National_Highway_1_(India)) from Srinagar and [NH3](/National_Highway_3_(India)) from [Manali](/Manali,_Himachal_Pradesh). A third road, the [Nimmu–Padam–Darcha road](/Nimmu%E2%80%93Padam%E2%80%93Darcha_road), is under construction.

Leh's airport, [Kushok Bakula Rimpochee Airport](/Kushok_Bakula_Rimpochee_Airport), offers daily flights to [Delhi](/Delhi) and weekly flights to Srinagar and Jammu. The airport in Kargil, [Kargil Airport](/Kargil_Airport), is primarily used by the military, a point of contention for locals who want it opened for civilian flights.

## Demographics

The population of Ladakh is roughly split between its two original districts, Leh and Kargil. The sex ratio has seen a significant decline over the decades, particularly in urban areas, reflecting the influx of male seasonal laborers. About 84% of the population lives in villages.

